Men surveyed said they would also agree to limit abortion rights if the procedure was tied to Christian values, American influence or "Homosexual lifestyles."

The survey, released by the U.S.-funded Iraqi Center for Development and Democracy (ICDD) - which was sparked by a move by Iraq's Parliament to ban abortion - found there was a general belief it should be illegal for women to abort because it leads to infertility.

More than 49 percent of men polled said they thought banning abortions would decrease the rate of infertility.

Asked whether a legal ban would end the practice, 14.5 percent - with no explanation why - said yes.

Forty- seven percent of men wanted a ban while 23 percent still did not know whether they supported or opposed a ban.

Women also polled felt women should not have the option to abort, but that was because they believed if they did, their fertility would decline - not because of infanticide or moral reasons.

The majority of both sexes believed a legal ban would reduce this perception of infertility among women, but many respondents did not understand that the study examined abortion of first and second trimester pregnancies.

The most striking view from both men and women was the strong belief - shared by politicians and Islamist groups - that government-imposed restrictions prior to 1991 resulted in a low level of abortion.
